&gt; <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The concern for diversion of fissiles from breeding<br>
and reprocessing sources is not so much subnational<br>
orgs (which IS a problem), but ~national~ diversion,<br>
where a government (or agency of government)<br>
clandestinely diverts material (within the statistical<br>
&quot;noise&quot; of inventory auditing) as feedstock for a<br>
weapons program.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 Valid concern. Another argument for a supra-national oversight of nuclear technology -unless the protestors are the sort who want <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>no</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> nuclear technology instead of safe nuclear technology, and that seems to be the major thrust of protests.<br>
Practically every concern can be addressed this way. Either totally ban all relevant technology &amp; sciences, or enact multinational controls.<br>
 Everything from safety &amp; accounting of breeder fuels, dismantled warhead pits and NPR thrust bombs, to space mission profits &amp; property rights in space are calls for multinational controls.<br>
This still doesn't completely address the problem of nuclear weapons. Nations can still make their own industry to make weapons. This is a completely separate concern, and not a valid reason to push for complete bans of nuclear technology.<br>
<br>
 (As a world federalist, I'd say that weapons &amp; war are another and perhaps the biggest concern which requires multinational oversight, but I'll leave that out. Even if there were an international nuclear oversight body and an active, useful civil nuclear technology industry up to &amp; including NPR ships, I don't at all put it past megalomaniac politicians &amp; generals to duplicate the technlogies to continue weapons building. Again, dumb down and try to ban all associated technologies &amp; sciences?)<br>
